I'll try to explain it in the most practical way again:

I've loaded a SmartContract on Berkeley. You can find it at this link: https://berkeley.minaexplorer.com/wallet/B62qqGffLjSuSs8XUSkP59UmskDtKF8jp2dNXzLS3GNAZNu7FeCFH7c

I've saved both the SmartContract code and the Verification Key:

Here's the `smartContract.js` code:

```javascript
...
export class Square extends SmartContract {
    @state(Field) num = State<Field>();

    init() {
        super.init();
        this.num.set(Field(3));
    }

    @method update(square: Field) {
        const currentState = this.num.get();
        this.num.assertEquals(currentState);
        square.assertEquals(currentState.mul(currentState));
        this.num.set(square);
    }
}
...
```

And here's the `verificationKey.json`:

```json
{
    "data": "AAC2...qR0=",
    "hash": "1459-..0962"
}
```

Now, I'd like to call the `update` method. However, instead of using `.compile()` (which takes a lot of time), I want to use the previously saved Verification Key (`verificationKey.json`). What are the practical options to achieve this?

```javascript
...

import { Square } from './smartContract.js';

const verificationKey = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('verificationKey.json', 'utf-8'));

Square.setVerification(verificationKey); // ?
// Square.compile()

const publicKey = PublicKey.fromBase58(...);
const zk = new Square(publicKey);
const txn1 = await Mina.transaction(
    {
        'feePayerKey': PrivateKey.fromBase58(...), 
        'fee': 100_000_000,
        'memo': 'hello world'
    },
    () => { zk.update(Field(6561)); }
);

await txn1.prove();
await txn1
    .sign([PrivateKey.fromBase58(...)])
    .send();
```

@andreas the Kimchi book also describes the differences between a Prover and a Verifier and talks about a prover index for proving and verification index (key) for verifying: https://o1-labs.github.io/proof-systems/specs/kimchi.html#proof-creation

